nicans in their struggles for democracy and social justice. While the dictatorship of Rafael Trujillo saw the sport as a means of cementing its power at home and abroad, the Dominican people fashioned an emancipated civic sphere by seeing their potential for democratic success in their compatriots’ baseball success. Later, Dominicans articulated demands for democracy, economic opportunity, and civil rights through successful calls for public support of amateur and professional baseball. Today, Dominicans continue to demand that incentives for the baseball industry foster human as well as economic development. A revelatory and innovative history, Pitching Democracy restores agency to the Dominican people and honors their true love of the game.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aBaseballxEconomic aspectszDominican Republic. 0aBaseballxPolitical aspectszDominican Republic. 0aBaseballzDominican RepublicxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aDominican Republic, Baseball, Democracy, Development, Cold War, Major League Baseball, Trujillo Molina, Rafael Leonidas, Joaquín Balaguer, Juan Bosch, Latin American Studies, Sports, Sports History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079782440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32676340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477326770423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477326770/original  a978-3-11-079782-4  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK